SIMPLE: practicable
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Practicable
<hw>Prac"ti*ca*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>practicare</ets> to act, transact, fr. L. <ets>practicus</ets>
active, Gr. <?/: cf. F. <ets>practicable</ets>, <ets>pratiquer</ets> to
practice. See <er>Practical</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That may be
practiced or performed; capable of being done or accomplished with
available means or resources; feasible; <as>as, a <ex>practicable</ex>
method; a <ex>practicable</ex> aim; a <ex>practicable</ex>
good.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Capable of being used; passable; <as>as, a
<ex>practicable</ex> weapon; a <ex>practicable</ex> road.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Practicable breach</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a
breach which admits of approach and entrance by an assailing
party.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Possible; feasible. -- <er>Practicable</er>,
<er>Possible</er>. A thing may be <xex>possible</xex>, i. e., not
forbidden by any law of nature, and yet may not now be
<xex>practicable</xex> for want of the means requisite to its
performance.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Prac"ti*ca*ble*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos> --
<wf>Prac"ti*ca*bly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Practical</ent>⟦br⟧
